# testrun selftest manifest. Every mode carries one record that must pass and one
# that must fail, so a run proves the runner accepts a correct expectation and
# rejects a wrong one. The names ending in _bad are the deliberate failures;
# tools/testrun-selftest.sh asserts the failing set is exactly that set.

test run_ok
mode run
file examples/hello.dusk
out hello, world\n
---
test run_bad
mode run
file examples/hello.dusk
out this is the wrong output\n
---
test runraw_ok
mode run_raw
file examples/slicebound.dusk
ok false
out 2\n
err_has index out of bounds
---
test runraw_bad
mode run_raw
file examples/slicebound.dusk
ok true
---
test checkfail_ok
mode check_fail
file examples/break_fail.dusk
err_has break is only legal inside a loop
---
test checkfail_bad
mode check_fail
file examples/hello.dusk
---
test checkok_ok
mode check_ok
file examples/hello.dusk
---
test checkok_bad
mode check_ok
file examples/break_fail.dusk
---
test buildfail_ok
mode build_fail
file examples/methodunresolved_fail.dusk
err_has no method 'toString' on type 'V'
---
test buildfail_bad
mode build_fail
file examples/hello.dusk
---
test tool_ok
mode tool
argv version
code 0
out dusk 1.8.1\n
---
test tool_bad
mode tool
argv version
out this is not the version line\n
---
test errabsent_ok
mode check_fail
file examples/break_fail.dusk
err_has break is only legal inside a loop
err_absent this fragment never appears in the diagnostic
---
test errabsent_bad
mode check_fail
file examples/break_fail.dusk
err_absent break is only legal inside a loop
---
test special_ok
mode special
special installed_layout
---
test special_bad
mode special
special dawn_get
